---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is the difference between static and dynamic secrets in Vault?",
    answer: "Static secrets (KV engine) are pre-created credentials you store in Vault — like API keys or service passwords. They don't expire unless you manually rotate them. Dynamic secrets are generated on-demand by Vault for a specific TTL (e.g., 1 hour) and automatically revoked when they expire. Dynamic database credentials mean no shared passwords, no credential sprawl, and automatic rotation without human intervention."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I inject Vault secrets into Kubernetes pods?",
    answer: "Use the Vault Agent Injector (installed via Helm). Add annotations to your pod spec: vault.hashicorp.com/agent-inject: 'true', vault.hashicorp.com/role: 'my-app', and vault.hashicorp.com/agent-inject-secret-config.txt: 'secret/data/myapp/config'. The sidecar container authenticates to Vault using the pod's Kubernetes service account and writes secrets to a shared tmpfs volume at /vault/secrets/."
  },
  {
    question: "What is Vault Agent and how does it work?",
    answer: "Vault Agent is a client-side daemon that handles authentication, secret renewal, and templating on behalf of your application. It authenticates to Vault once, caches the token, renews it before expiry, and can render secrets into files using Go templates. In Kubernetes it runs as a sidecar injected by the Vault Agent Injector webhook."
  },
  {
    question: "How does App Role authentication work in Vault?",
    answer: "App Role is designed for machine/application authentication. You create a role with policies attached, generating a RoleID (public, like a username) and SecretID (private, like a password). Your application presents both to Vault at /auth/approle/login to receive a Vault token. SecretIDs can be single-use, time-limited, and bound to specific CIDR ranges for security."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I use Vault with Docker Compose locally?",
    answer: "Run Vault in dev mode: 'docker run --cap-add=IPC_LOCK -e VAULT_DEV_ROOT_TOKEN_ID=root -p 8200:8200 vault'. Set VAULT_ADDR=http://localhost:8200 and VAULT_TOKEN=root in your app's environment. Dev mode starts pre-configured with a KV v2 engine at secret/ and does not persist data — ideal for local development and testing."
  },
  {
    question: "Vault vs AWS Secrets Manager — which should I use?",
    answer: "Use AWS Secrets Manager if you're AWS-native and want managed rotation for RDS/Redshift with minimal ops overhead. Use Vault if you need multi-cloud secrets management, non-AWS dynamic credentials (Postgres on-prem, SSH, PKI), fine-grained policies, or want to avoid vendor lock-in. Vault has a steeper learning curve but significantly more flexibility for complex environments."
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="HashiCorp Vault: Secrets Management Patterns & Setup Guide"
  description="HashiCorp Vault secrets management guide: dev server setup, KV secrets engine, dynamic database credentials, Kubernetes auth, App Role, and secrets injection patterns."
  tool="HashiCorp Vault, secrets management, KV secrets, dynamic credentials, Kubernetes Vault, App Role"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "HashiCorp Vault: Secrets Management Patterns & Setup Guide",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/vault-hashicorp-secrets",
    "description": "HashiCorp Vault secrets management guide: dev server setup, KV secrets engine, dynamic database credentials, Kubernetes auth, App Role, and secrets injection patterns.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">HashiCorp Vault: Secrets Management Patterns & Setup Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">HashiCorp Vault is the industry-standard secrets management platform for storing, rotating, and dynamically generating credentials. This guide covers everything from local dev setup to production patterns for Kubernetes, dynamic database credentials, and App Role authentication.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> KV v2 static secrets</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Dynamic database credentials</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Kubernetes native injection</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> PKI certificate management</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Multi-cloud support</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">What is Vault and Why Use It?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Environment variables and config files are the most common way teams handle secrets — and one of the most dangerous. Secrets end up in Docker images, CI logs, and git history. Vault centralizes secrets with fine-grained access policies, full audit logs, and automatic rotation. Every secret access is logged: who requested it, when, from which IP.</p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Vault's killer feature is <strong>dynamic secrets</strong>: instead of a shared database password, Vault generates a unique username/password pair per application instance with a 1-hour TTL. When the lease expires, Vault automatically revokes the credentials on the database.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Dev Server Quickstart</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Start Vault dev server (in-memory, no persistence)
vault server -dev -dev-root-token-id=root

# In another terminal
export VAULT_ADDR='http://127.0.0.1:8200'
export VAULT_TOKEN='root'

# Check status
vault status

# Write a secret
vault kv put secret/myapp/db password="s3cr3t" username="app"

# Read it back
vault kv get secret/myapp/db

# Get a specific field
vault kv get -field=password secret/myapp/db</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">KV Secrets Engine v2</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">KV v2 adds versioning and soft-delete to static secrets:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Enable KV v2 at a custom path
vault secrets enable -path=myapp kv-v2

# Write secrets
vault kv put myapp/production \
  db_password="prod-secret" \
  api_key="sk-abc123"

# Read a specific version
vault kv get -version=2 myapp/production

# List all secrets at a path
vault kv list myapp/

# Rollback to a previous version
vault kv rollback -version=1 myapp/production</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Dynamic Database Credentials</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Enable database secrets engine
vault secrets enable database

# Configure PostgreSQL connection
vault write database/config/my-postgresql \
    plugin_name=postgresql-database-plugin \
    allowed_roles="my-role" \
    connection_url="postgresql://&#123;&#123;username&#125;&#125;:&#123;&#123;password&#125;&#125;@localhost:5432/mydb" \
    username="vault-root" \
    password="root-password"

# Create a role with TTL
vault write database/roles/my-role \
    db_name=my-postgresql \
    creation_statements="CREATE ROLE \"&#123;&#123;name&#125;&#125;\" WITH LOGIN PASSWORD '&#123;&#123;password&#125;&#125;' VALID UNTIL '&#123;&#123;expiration&#125;&#125;'; GRANT SELECT ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO \"&#123;&#123;name&#125;&#125;\";" \
    default_ttl="1h" \
    max_ttl="24h"

# Generate credentials (your app does this)
vault read database/creds/my-role</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Vault Agent for Kubernetes Secrets Injection</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Install Vault via Helm with injector enabled
helm repo add hashicorp https://helm.releases.hashicorp.com
helm install vault hashicorp/vault \
  --set "injector.enabled=true" \
  --set "server.dev.enabled=true"

# Annotate your deployment to inject secrets
# In pod spec annotations:
# vault.hashicorp.com/agent-inject: "true"
# vault.hashicorp.com/role: "my-app"
# vault.hashicorp.com/agent-inject-secret-config: "secret/data/myapp/config"
# vault.hashicorp.com/agent-inject-template-config: |
#   &#123;&#123;- with secret "secret/data/myapp/config" -&#125;&#125;
#   export DB_PASSWORD="{{ .Data.data.password }}"
#   &#123;&#123;- end &#125;&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">App Role Authentication</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Enable App Role auth
vault auth enable approle

# Create a role
vault write auth/approle/role/my-app \
    token_ttl=1h \
    token_max_ttl=4h \
    secret_id_ttl=10m \
    secret_id_num_uses=1

# Get the RoleID (share with app config)
vault read auth/approle/role/my-app/role-id

# Generate a SecretID (request fresh one per deploy)
vault write -f auth/approle/role/my-app/secret-id

# App login
vault write auth/approle/login \
    role_id="..." \
    secret_id="..."</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Vault vs AWS Secrets Manager vs Doppler</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Aspect</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Vault</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">AWS Secrets Manager</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Doppler</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Dynamic secrets</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes (all engines)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">RDS/Redshift only</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Multi-cloud</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">AWS only</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Self-hosted</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes (HCP Vault also)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Developer UX</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Complex</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Good (AWS native)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Excellent</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">Cost</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Free OSS / HCP paid</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">$0.40/secret/mo</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Free tier + paid</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <ToolPageCta />
  <FaqSection faqs={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
